{{Unreferenced|date=August 2011}}

In [[geology]], '''aquatic succession''' is the process in which a glacial lake dries up. Over the lifespan of a [[glacier]] it dissolves into a body of water. Aquatic succession is the continuing step of that solid water-turned-lake melting into the ground and further disappearing into [[nothingness|oblivion]]. The lakes sometime become underground lakes or rivers. The water tends to remain part of the local [[hydrosphere]] by percolating into [[aquifers]].



