{{other uses}} [[File:Top of Rock Cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Midtown Manhattan]] during the blue hour]] [[File:Seascape after sunset denoised.jpg|thumb|Praia da Ursa, [[Sintra]], [[Portugal]]: A wide-angle view of the seascape during the blue hour]]
The '''blue hour''' (from [[French language|French]] {{lang|fr|l'heure bleue}})<ref>{{cite book |last=Verfaillie |first=Roland |title=L'heure Bleue |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P56JAwAAQBAJ |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=P56JAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA5 5] |year=2011 |location=San Francisco |publisher=Purple Onion Press}}</ref>{{efn|A similar [[calque]] {{lang|es|la hora azul}} is used in [[Spanish language|Spanish]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}}} is the period of [[twilight]] in the [[dawn|morning]] or [[dusk|evening]], during the civil and nautical stages, when the [[Sun]] is at a significant [[altitude (astronomy)|depth]] below the [[horizon]] and residual, indirect [[sunlight]] takes on a predominantly [[Rayleigh scattering|blue shade]].
When the [[sky]] is clear, the blue hour can be a colorful spectacle, with the [[diffuse sky radiation|indirect sunlight]] tinting the sky yellow, orange, [[Belt of Venus|red]], and [[Earth's shadow|blue]]. This effect is caused by the relative [[photon diffusion|diffusibility]] of shorter [[wavelengths]] (bluer rays) of [[visible light]] versus the longer wavelengths (redder rays).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} During the blue "hour", which typically lasts roughly 20 minutes (depending on [[latitude]]), red light passes through space while blue light is [[scattering|scattered]] in the atmosphere, and thus reaches Earth's surface.
Many artists value this period for the quality of the [[hard and soft light|soft light]]. Although the blue hour does not have an official definition, the blue color spectrum is most prominent when the Sun is between 4° and 8° below the horizon.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blue Hour – Magic Hour |url=https://www.timeanddate.com/astronomy/blue-hour.html |publisher=timeanddate.com |access-date=16 October 2017}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Belt of Venus]] * [[Golden hour (photography)]] * [[Green flash]] * [[Midnight sun]] * [[Polar night]] * ''[[Summer Evening on Skagen's Southern Beach]]'' * [[Twilight]]
