{{Human impact on the environment}}
[[Category:Global issues| ]] [[Category:Global inequality]]

{{refimprove|date=December 2009}} [[Image:Hells Half Acre.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Hell's Half Acre Lava Field]], [[Idaho]], [[United States|USA]].]] [[Image:Iceland (3), Reykjanes peninsula.JPG|thumb|300px|Barren waste of lava fields at [[Reykjanes|Reykjanes Peninsula]], [[Iceland]].]] A '''lava field''', also called a '''lava plain''' or '''lava bed''', is a large expanse of nearly flat-lying [[lava]] flows. Such features are generally composed of highly fluid [[basalt]] lava, and can extend for tens or even hundreds of miles across the underlying terrain. The extent of large lava fields is most readily grasped from the air or in satellite photos, where their typically dark, nearly black color contrasts sharply with the rest of the landscape.
According to the US Geological Survey, [[monogenetic volcanic field]]s are collections of [[cinder cones]], and/or [[Maar]] vents and associated lava flows and pyroclastic deposits. Sometimes a [[stratovolcano]]<ref name=USGS>{{cite web|url=http://vulcan.wr.usgs.gov/Glossary/VolcanicFields/framework.html|title=Volcanic Fields|accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref> is at the center of the field, as at the [[San Francisco Volcanic Field]] in Arizona. Monogenetic volcano fields have systematic growth patterns that suggest they represent single magmatic systems in the same way that stratovolcanoes do, but monogenetic volcanoes grow laterally rather than vertically (Wood and Shoan, 1984){{Full citation needed|date=March 2018}}. Detailed mapping indicates that some cinder cones in monogenetic fields (e.g., [[Cima volcanic field]], California, and Timber Mountain Volcanic Field, Nevada) may have had multiple eruptions separated by tens to hundreds of thousands of years (Wells, et al., 1989){{Full citation needed|date=March 2018}}. Thus, some monogenetic cones may actually be [[Polygenetic volcanic field|polygenetic]]. This possibility differs from observations of historic eruptions (Wood, 1979){{Full citation needed|date=March 2018}}, and is physically difficult to understand because cinder cone conduits are narrow and must solidify within a few years of eruption. Nonetheless, such multiple eruptions appear to have happened at least twice: Other cinder cones need to be closely reexamined.<ref name=USGS/>
Some of the most ancient geological remnants of basaltic [[plain]]s lie in [[Canada]]'s [[Canadian Shield|Precambrian Shield]]. Eruption of plateau lavas near the [[Coppermine River]] southwest of [[Coronation Gulf]] in the [[Arctic]], built an extensive plateau about 1200 million years ago with an area of about {{convert|170000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, representing a volume of lavas of at least {{convert|500000|km3|mi3|abbr=on}}. The lavas are thought to have originated from a mantle plume center called the [[Mackenzie hotspot]].{{cn|date=April 2014}}
==Notable examples== *[[Boring Lava Field]] ([[United States]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_america/boring_lava.html|title=Boring Lava Field|accessdate=2014-01-26|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207112612/http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_america/boring_lava.html|archivedate=2012-02-07|df=}}</ref> *[[Harrat Rahat]], which threatened the city of [[Medina]] in the 13th century ([[Saudi Arabia]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsabulletin.gsapubs.org/content/101/1/71.abstract|title=Harrat Rahat|accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref> *[[Hell's Half Acre Lava Field]] ([[Idaho]], [United States])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blm.gov/id/st/en/visit_and_play/places_to_see/upper_snake_field/Hell_s_Half_Acre_Lava_Trail.html|title=Hell_s_Half_Acre_Lava_Trail|accessdate=2014-01-26|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201181838/http://www.blm.gov/id/st/en/visit_and_play/places_to_see/upper_snake_field/Hell_s_Half_Acre_Lava_Trail.html|archivedate=2014-02-01|df=}}</ref> *[[Reykjanes]], [[Iceland]] (peninsula is mainly a barren waste of lava fields)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://is.geoview.info/lava_field_reykjanes_peninsula,16453295p|title=Reykjanes Peninsula|accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref> *[[St. George, Utah|St. George]], [[Utah]], [[United States]] (city built around fields and bluffs covered in lava rocks)
